body:
#### Issue details
Hey @badlogic sorry to bother you again, but I'm having troubles with this recent commit too https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/commit/a0e584f160042d355b51558f3d43f143cb17fc84#diff-040a0bcb5d798c1906e75ea04d512d8a2ce33b694b8b1c4fe8edd6e6ffd9a2c5R73

In brief the `GLFWFramebufferSizeCallback` is called outside the main loop, this is very useful becuase the application can render and update its view when window is resized (otherwise the window content will look frozen). However with this change you post all the updates to the main loop and this will destory all benefits coming from the callback. Moreover, this create a crazy behavior becuase after the mouse is released `ApplicationListener#resize` function is called hundred times at same time which create a very bad experience. I usually get a `not responding` window while resizing becuase of this.

#### Reproduction steps/code
The issue can be reproduced easly in Windows OS with a very basic application:
```Java
    private static class TestApp implements ApplicationListener {

        @Override
        public void create() {

        }

        @Override
        public void resize(int width, int height) {
            System.out.println("Resize");
        }

        @Override
        public void render() {

        }

        @Override
        public void pause() {

        }

        @Override
        public void resume() {

        }

        @Override
        public void dispose() {

        }
    }
```
During window resize the rendering is froozen and the resize function is not called until you release the mouse. After, the resize method will be invoked hundred of times. It might produce a `no responding` window.

#### Version of libGDX and/or relevant dependencies
latest libGDX 1.10.1-SNAPSHOT

#### Please select the affected platforms
- [ ] Android
- [ ] iOS
- [ ] HTML/GWT
- [X] Windows
- [ ] Linux
- [ ] macOS
